00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:46.480
OK.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.320
So, can I prove this?

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:50.290
Let me try.

00:02:50.290 --> 00:02:51.880
We'll start here,
at the beginning.

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:56.330
That's yeast,
saccharomyces cerevisiae,

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:59.430
sugar-eating mushroom
that makes beer.

00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:02.100
The name is a little
on the nose perhaps.

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:06.410
But what yeast
does, fundamentally,

00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:10.965
is eats sugar and then excretes
carbon dioxide and ethanol,

00:03:10.965 --> 00:03:12.140
the alcohol that we drink.

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:16.160
Don't panic.

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:22.772
There's only one more that looks
like this in the whole deck.

00:03:22.772 --> 00:03:24.480
This is only interesting
for two reasons.

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:27.190
This is a yeast metabolism.

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:28.890
This is what made
sure that I was not

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:29.890
going to be a biologist.

00:03:29.890 --> 00:03:31.934
This made sure that I
was going to be a writer.

00:03:31.934 --> 00:03:33.600
But two things I want
to point out here.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.860
The green, the little green down
in the lower right, is energy.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:42.710
ATP is the way a yeast
and you and I make energy.

00:03:42.710 --> 00:03:45.840
And it's what we use for-- it's
the power source in our bodies.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.730
So this is yeast taking in
glucose, up in the upper left,

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:49.640
turning it into ATP.

00:03:49.640 --> 00:03:52.170
But then the box is
the interesting part.

00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:55.640
Because the box is
yeast using an enzyme

00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:58.910
called alcohol dehydrogenase
1 to turn something called

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:01.390
acetaldehyde into ethanol
and then excreting it.

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:05.520
But also using alcohol
dehydrogenase 2

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.900
to take that ethanol and
convert it back to acetaldehyde.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:14.000
Basically, yeast eats its
own poop is the point.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.760
But that brings to rise
an important question.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.130
Why does yeast make alcohol?

00:04:21.130 --> 00:04:23.880
Not philosophically, it's not
like an existential question.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:26.805
But evolutionarily, why
does yeast make alcohol?

00:04:26.805 --> 00:04:29.760
So there's two possibilities,
prompted by that little box.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:32.800
One of them is that ethanol
is chemical warfare.

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:35.390
What do you do when you
want to clean out a cut?

00:04:35.390 --> 00:04:36.370
Use alcohol.

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:38.310
Alcohol's really good
at killing microbes.

00:04:38.310 --> 00:04:39.400
It's a microbicide.

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:44.009
So maybe yeast is using ethanol
to kill competitors locally.

00:04:44.009 --> 00:04:46.050
Yeast can tolerate really
high levels of ethanol.

00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:46.980
Other microbes can't.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:51.030
It makes its own
chemical weapon.

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:53.070
So that's what ADH
1 suggests, right?

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:57.100
Or ADH 2 says well, maybe
ethanol is just a food source.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:01.680
It's storing away nuts for the
winter, in the microbial way,

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:02.460
right?

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:04.360
So which is it?

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:06.440
How do you figure that out?

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:09.432
That is what this
guy tried to do.

00:05:09.432 --> 00:05:11.140
This is a researcher
named Steven Benner.

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:13.137
He invented a field
called paleogenetics.

00:05:13.137 --> 00:05:14.803
Paleogenetics is a
little bit like-- you

00:05:14.803 --> 00:05:16.511
know how linguists
will try to figure out

00:05:16.511 --> 00:05:18.270
what the first word
for something was,

00:05:18.270 --> 00:05:20.897
by looking at what the word
is in all different languages

00:05:20.897 --> 00:05:22.480
and finding what the
similarities are,

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:24.270
and trying to back trace it?

00:05:24.270 --> 00:05:26.970
He figured out you could do
the same thing for enzymes.

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:29.350
That if you would take all
the samples of that enzyme

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:30.849
from a bunch of
different organisms,

00:05:30.849 --> 00:05:32.800
in this case
Saccharomyces cerevisiae

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:34.580
yeast and the
water-related species,

00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:37.760
look at the various alcohol
dehydrogenase enzymes,

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:40.440
you could build, as he
did-- his team did--

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:45.550
12 different versions
of the primordial ADH,

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:46.980
what the first one looked like.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:47.814
They called it adhA.

00:05:47.814 --> 00:05:49.896
They didn't know exactly
how it was going to work,

00:05:49.896 --> 00:05:51.360
so they had 12
different versions.

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:54.126
And what they wanted to
do was run the equation.

00:05:54.126 --> 00:05:55.500
Let it run, look
at the kinetics,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:56.640
and see what it wanted to do.

00:05:56.640 --> 00:05:58.514
Did it want to make
acetaldehyde into ethanol

00:05:58.514 --> 00:06:01.190
or make ethanol
into acetaldehyde.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:02.630
So they did it.

00:06:02.630 --> 00:06:03.670
And what happened?

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:05.800
Turned out adhA was a
lot more like the one

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:07.860
that made the ethanol.

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:09.520
Yeast wants to make ethanol.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:10.830
So problem solved.

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:13.310
Chemical weapon, right?

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:14.310
No, of course not.

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:16.180
It's not that easy.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:18.590
I said that yeast eats sugar.

00:06:18.590 --> 00:06:20.840
150 million years ago,
when yeast are first

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:22.484
figuring this out,
where's the sugar?

00:06:22.484 --> 00:06:24.400
Sugar cane hasn't evolved
yet, because grasses

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:25.233
haven't evolved yet.

00:06:25.233 --> 00:06:26.790
Sugar cane is a grass.

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:31.930
Well, plants, where yeasts
live, were mostly conifers.

00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:34.610
They were like pine trees,
like on the right there.

00:06:34.610 --> 00:06:38.657
No, my right.

00:06:38.657 --> 00:06:40.990
Yeast probably lived exposed
to the air on these things,

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.210
on tree sap exudates,
on little blurbs of sap.

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:45.730
Like when you come
near a pine tree

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:47.102
and you get sap on your hand.

00:06:47.102 --> 00:06:48.310
That's where the yeast lived.

00:06:48.310 --> 00:06:49.998
And so, because
ethanol is volatile,

00:06:49.998 --> 00:06:51.414
it wants to
evaporate-- and that's

00:06:51.414 --> 00:06:54.350
going to be important later
as a property-- that's

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:57.040
a really good property to
have in a waste product.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:58.950
That's perfect sewage.

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:00.760
Have ethanol, and
then it evaporates.

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:03.594
But then about 100 million
years later-- sorry,

00:07:03.594 --> 00:07:05.760
about 50 million years
later, 100 million years ago,

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:08.310
in the Cretaceous
period, the fruity plants

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:10.920
take over from the pine trees,
the fruiting flowering plants.

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:12.820
Those are the angiosperms.

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:14.300
The other plant
there is amborella,

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:15.870
it's the very first angiosperm.

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:20.324
And yeast now are pre-adapted to
live inside those fruits, where

00:07:20.324 --> 00:07:22.240
all the simple sugar is
that they want to eat,

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:24.420
because they can tolerate
higher level levels of ethanol.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:25.794
They're making
their own ethanol,

00:07:25.794 --> 00:07:27.860
and they can hang out
inside that fruit.

00:07:27.860 --> 00:07:30.630
So they look pre-evolved,
they look ready.

00:07:30.630 --> 00:07:33.160
What it actually is
is a coincidence.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:35.570
But because they're
adapted to do that,

00:07:35.570 --> 00:07:37.409
they have the luck
to do what needs

00:07:37.409 --> 00:07:38.700
to be done in a changing world.

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:41.610
Because the other animals that
couldn't handle the change

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:44.560
to angiosperms, to flowering
fruiting plants, went extinct.

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:47.960
It was an extinction level
event for like-- well, let's

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:48.970
put it this way.

00:07:48.970 --> 00:07:50.650
The dinosaurs that
figured out how

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:53.250
to deal with fruiting
flowering plants are birds.

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:59.390
The point I want to make
about this mostly-- other

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:02.490
than I just kind of think
it's a cool set of deductions

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.120
from the lab-- is
that fermentation

00:08:05.120 --> 00:08:07.990
happens without us.

00:08:07.990 --> 00:08:08.950
It doesn't need us.

00:08:08.950 --> 00:08:12.124
If yeast makes
ethanol in the forest,

00:08:12.124 --> 00:08:14.040
does anyone get drunk
to hear it or something.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:16.676
Right, like if nobody's
there, it still happens.

00:08:16.676 --> 00:08:17.800
There's still fermentation.

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:18.364
It occurs.

00:08:18.364 --> 00:08:20.280
It occurred for millions
and millions of years

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:23.640
before human beings
came on the scene.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:25.790
But then we did.

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:30.010
So this is a shard
of a pot that's

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:33.860
9,000 or 10,000 years old,
found in an archaeological site

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:34.980
in China called Jiahu.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:36.760
Jiahu's a really
interesting site.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:40.270
It's one of the places where the
first instances of rice being

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:41.864
consumed by human
beings was found.

00:08:41.864 --> 00:08:43.280
It's one of the
first places where

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:44.904
there was evidence
of written language.

00:08:44.904 --> 00:08:46.880
It's one of the
oldest places where

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:48.400
they found musical instruments.

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:52.620
It's one of the places where
civilization began, where

00:08:52.620 --> 00:08:56.550
all of the things that we
think make us civilized people

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:57.954
happened first.

00:08:57.954 --> 00:08:59.370
Well, one of the
things they found

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:01.950
was this pot with some
weird residue inside.

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:04.260
You can guess, probably
it's not a spoiler to say,

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:05.600
what that residue's going to be.

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:07.475
But they didn't know
what it was at the time.

00:09:07.475 --> 00:09:09.770
So, the researchers who
were working the site

00:09:09.770 --> 00:09:13.220
sent for this analytical
chemist, a guy named Patrick

00:09:13.220 --> 00:09:15.616
McGovern, he works at the
University of Pennsylvania.

00:09:15.616 --> 00:09:17.490
He ran a bunch of tests--
gas chromatography,

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:19.910
mass spectroscopy, Feigl spot
test, he shot lasers at it.

00:09:19.910 --> 00:09:21.284
He you did all
the cool stuff you

00:09:21.284 --> 00:09:25.110
can do if you have a lab at
Penn and found three things.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:28.170
Not ethanol, I mentioned
ethanol's volatile.

00:09:28.170 --> 00:09:28.980
Ethanol evaporates.

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:31.590
So even in the oldest samples,
even in the ones like the Roman

00:09:31.590 --> 00:09:33.590
amphoras that they know
were used to carry wine,

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:34.881
they almost never find ethanol.

00:09:34.881 --> 00:09:36.050
They find other stuff.

00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:38.300
What he found was three things.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:42.780
Beeswax, which you only
find if there's honey.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:44.910
Rice, he found traces of rice.

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:47.310
And tartrates-- tartaric acid.

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:48.950
From anywhere else
at any other time

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:52.150
that would probably
have meant grapes.

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:53.936
But not in China,
not 10,000 years ago.

00:09:53.936 --> 00:09:55.560
They had grapes, they
had wild species,

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:57.450
but they weren't common.

00:09:57.450 --> 00:09:59.620
McGovern thinks it
was probably hawthorn,

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:01.660
which he says is
like a chalky apple.

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:04.080
It's a fruit that
has sugar in it.

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.959
Now if you mix all that stuff
together and ground it up

00:10:06.959 --> 00:10:09.000
and let it sit, you'd have
a hard time keeping it

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:10.850
from fermenting.

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:13.275
The wild yeast, the
ambient yeast in the air,

00:10:13.275 --> 00:10:14.150
would grab onto that.

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:15.080
There's a lot of sugar in there.

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:16.663
They would want to
make it into booze.

00:10:16.663 --> 00:10:21.580
What McGovern had found was
the mother Eve of booze.

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:23.490
Honey makes mead,
rice make sake,

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:26.020
fruit makes wine and brandy.

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:28.830
It's the oldest-- the evidence
that he found on this shard,

00:10:28.830 --> 00:10:31.315
it's the oldest example of
human controlled fermentation

00:10:31.315 --> 00:10:32.520
that anybody's ever found.

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:33.700
10,000 years.

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:35.490
I've held this.

00:10:35.490 --> 00:10:40.110
It's in his office, it's sitting
in a Ziploc on his shelf.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.790
And I asked to hold it,
and he put on gloves,

00:10:42.790 --> 00:10:44.790
he made me put on gloves,
he opened the thing.

00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:45.873
I mean, it was a big deal.

00:10:45.873 --> 00:10:46.800
But it was a big deal.

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:49.090
It's the oldest
thing I've ever held.

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:54.050
And it did give the sense
of a profound connection

00:10:54.050 --> 00:10:57.076
to the first home brewer, right?

00:10:57.076 --> 00:10:59.200
Whatever the ritual was,
whatever the ceremony was,

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:00.283
this is where it happened.

00:11:00.283 --> 00:11:01.990
This thing.

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:03.000
10,000 years.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.890
That's how long we've
been at it, at least.

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:08.740
Taming this natural
process, domesticating it,

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:11.900
domesticating yeast, while the
yeast domesticated us, right?

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:13.610
Please give me more sugar.

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:15.830
I will roll over with my
belly up and wag my tail

00:11:15.830 --> 00:11:17.330
if you will just
give me more sugar.

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:21.070
That's the key.

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:23.660
Here's the only other slide.

00:11:23.660 --> 00:11:26.900
Does anybody recognize this?

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:27.760
It's sugar, yeah.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.130
It's glucose, exactly.

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:30.520
Simplest of simple sugars.

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:33.140
Six carbons in a
hexagon, some hydrogens

00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:35.880
and oxygens dangling
off the corners.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:38.770
This is the most important
molecule on earth.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:41.150
Not water, water's
medium, not message.

00:11:41.150 --> 00:11:42.050
This is message.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:43.530
Sugar's power.

00:11:43.530 --> 00:11:45.840
Just about every
form of life on Earth

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:47.990
uses the energy stored
in all those chemical

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:52.100
bonds and the lines
to stay alive.

00:11:52.100 --> 00:11:55.230
Sugar's structure-- you get
variations in molecules,

00:11:55.230 --> 00:11:57.160
you get different
kinds of sugars.

00:11:57.160 --> 00:11:58.870
You can attach them together
in a bunch of different ways.

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:01.160
And instead of having a
monosaccharide, a single sugar,

00:12:01.160 --> 00:12:02.140
you can have
polysaccharides, you

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:03.660
can have bigger
and bigger sugars.

00:12:06.169 --> 00:12:08.710
Connect these glucose molecules
together in one specific way,

00:12:08.710 --> 00:12:09.800
and you get cellulose.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:14.210
The most common organic molecule
on earth-- wood, paper, right?

00:12:14.210 --> 00:12:16.310
It's just repeating
elements of that.

00:12:16.310 --> 00:12:17.710
That's the sub-unit.

00:12:17.710 --> 00:12:20.235
Connect that same molecule
in a different way,

00:12:20.235 --> 00:12:22.360
and you get the starches--
amylose and amylopectin.

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:28.280
Sugar is literally--
this is just an aside,

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:29.690
I'm going to do that a
lot-- sugar is literally

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:31.190
the backbone of our genes.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:32.650
Deoxyribonucleic acid?

00:12:32.650 --> 00:12:33.845
The ribo in there is ribose.

00:12:33.845 --> 00:12:35.140
It's a sugar.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:36.850
We're made of this.

00:12:36.850 --> 00:12:38.100
It's our storage medium.

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:39.490
So that's all neat, right?

00:12:39.490 --> 00:12:40.340
That's cool.

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:43.470
And like I said, yeast
eat simple sugars-- mono

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:46.690
and disaccharides primarily
excrete carbon dioxide,

00:12:46.690 --> 00:12:47.260
make ethanol.

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:52.260
So that's all fine, if you
have a source of simple sugar.

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:54.870
Apples have a lot of
those simple sugars.

00:12:54.870 --> 00:12:56.630
Honey, tons, right?

00:12:56.630 --> 00:12:59.380
Put honey out in water and
you automatically get mead.

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:02.146
Grapes, grapes are
awesome, 25% simple sugar.

00:13:02.146 --> 00:13:04.020
Every single varietal
of wine you've ever had

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:05.220
is one grape species.

00:13:05.220 --> 00:13:07.545
Vitis vinifera, lucky
enough to survive an ice age

00:13:07.545 --> 00:13:09.670
and show up in the Fertile
Crescent, Transcaucasian

00:13:09.670 --> 00:13:12.060
Mountain area, just about
when people wanted to plant

00:13:12.060 --> 00:13:13.600
stuff and make booze.

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:17.770
One researcher told me if human
beings had evolved on a Pacific

00:13:17.770 --> 00:13:20.000
island or had started
cities on Pacific Islands

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.507
instead of in the
Transcaucasian Mountains,

00:13:22.507 --> 00:13:24.840
then we'd have hundreds of
different species of coconut.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.930
And grape would be a rare thing
that you found in Whole Foods

00:13:26.930 --> 00:13:27.596
once in a while.

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:31.680
So that's all fine.

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:35.180
But what if your most easily
accessible agricultural product

00:13:35.180 --> 00:13:37.950
stores its sugar as starch?

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:39.590
Because here's the problem.

00:13:39.590 --> 00:13:43.610
You know how we in the room--
unless one of you is a mutant--

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:46.177
cannot digest cellulose.

00:13:46.177 --> 00:13:47.510
We just don't know how to do it.

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:48.620
But we can digest starch.

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:50.060
There's an enzyme in
our saliva that does.

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:51.476
There's an amylase,
an enzyme that

00:13:51.476 --> 00:13:54.000
digests starch, in our saliva
that begins that process.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.330
Yeast can't do either
of those things.

00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:00.265
So if it's grain or rice
or corn, this of barley,

00:14:00.265 --> 00:14:03.090
it just stores all
that sugar as starch.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:05.180
What do you do?

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:06.860
Grains are fascinating.

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:08.650
They're basically
little life bombs.

00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:10.510
There's an a plant
embryo in there

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:16.170
and then starch to store fuel,
like a yolk in an animal egg.

00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:18.650
That's what that starch is.

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:21.760
When it's time to grow, the
seeds-- the barley corns

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:23.970
or the grains--
make enzymes that

00:14:23.970 --> 00:14:26.060
convert that starch into sugar.

00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:28.020
The amylases that break it down.

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:32.780
And why would you
want to do that?

00:14:32.780 --> 00:14:34.950
Fermenting and distilling
eventually are like value adds,

00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:35.790
basically, right?

00:14:35.790 --> 00:14:37.710
You have a whole field
full of that stuff,

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:39.310
it's hard to get it to market.

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:40.816
But if you take
that whole field,

00:14:40.816 --> 00:14:42.440
and you turn into a
barrel of something

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:44.023
that you can actually
charge more for,

00:14:44.023 --> 00:14:45.719
it's easier to
get to the market.

00:14:45.719 --> 00:14:47.260
People want to pay
more money for it.

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:48.950
It's a value add.

00:14:48.950 --> 00:14:52.160
So the way that we
do that in the West

00:14:52.160 --> 00:14:55.630
is with a process called
malting, like single malt

00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:56.810
scotch.

00:14:56.810 --> 00:14:59.990
And malting basically is--
this is Glen Ord Malting,

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:00.910
it's owned by Diageo.

00:15:00.910 --> 00:15:01.700
It's in the north of Scotland.

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:03.760
Diageo is a big
transnational drinks company.

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:07.930
They do almost 84 million pounds
of barley into malt a year.

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:10.470
It's like seven trucks a
day, every day of the year.

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:11.980
It only takes about 11
people to run the plant.

00:15:11.980 --> 00:15:13.896
But basically what they're
doing in this place

00:15:13.896 --> 00:15:17.110
is tricking barley into
thinking that it's growing.

00:15:17.110 --> 00:15:18.300
They let it germinate.

00:15:18.300 --> 00:15:19.940
It grows a little bit.

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:22.302
It starts the biochemical
processes going and making

00:15:22.302 --> 00:15:24.510
those enzymes, converting
those starches into sugars.

00:15:24.510 --> 00:15:25.680
And then they
arrest the process.

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:27.660
They stop it, so they have
access to the enzymes.

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:29.120
And then you can mix it
in with other grains.

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:30.830
And you can make beer out of it.

00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:32.837
Distill beer and you get whisky.

00:15:32.837 --> 00:15:35.420
Basically, anything that we make
that's fermented or distilled

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:38.310
in the West, starts
with malt or the enzymes

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:41.570
that you can extract
from the malting process.

00:15:41.570 --> 00:15:46.260
That's fine, but what if
you were working with rice?

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:51.310
So if you're making sake or
rice wine, like in Japan,

00:15:51.310 --> 00:15:53.670
they don't use malting.

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:56.890
They actually polish away all
of the rice bran, the thing that

00:15:56.890 --> 00:15:59.660
makes rice brown, those are the
layers that make those enzymes.

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:02.320
What they do is they infect
the rice with another fungus--

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:04.890
yeast is a fungus.

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:06.642
The fungus is called koji.

00:16:06.642 --> 00:16:08.772
Have you heard of this?

00:16:08.772 --> 00:16:10.730
Some of the sake fans
probably know about koji.

00:16:10.730 --> 00:16:12.870
Koji is a fungus.

00:16:12.870 --> 00:16:14.354
It makes proteases and amylases.

00:16:14.354 --> 00:16:16.270
It breaks down proteins,
breaks down starches.

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:19.590
It's the basis for
almost every Asian food.

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:25.270
It's how they make tofu
and vinegar and sake.

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:26.622
It's an Aspergillus oryzae.

00:16:26.622 --> 00:16:28.330
And so if you know
anything about plants,

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:30.788
that would make you nervous
because most of the Aspergillus

00:16:30.788 --> 00:16:32.910
species are total bastards.

00:16:32.910 --> 00:16:35.844
They make aflatoxins,
they're carcinogenic.

00:16:35.844 --> 00:16:37.510
The clinical literature
includes phrases

00:16:37.510 --> 00:16:40.650
like, "bloody ball of
mucus in the lungs."

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.400
They're horrifying.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:43.334
But not koji.

00:16:43.334 --> 00:16:45.250
Koji has all the genes
that do all that stuff,

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:46.180
but they're all turned off.

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:48.013
It's domesticated, it's
another tame fungus.

00:16:48.013 --> 00:16:51.140
We tamed it to do
one thing-- make

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:53.160
rice sugary so yeast can eat it.

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:55.150
Been around since 300 BC.

00:16:55.150 --> 00:16:56.770
All right, so
fascinating process.

00:16:56.770 --> 00:17:00.100
So interesting in fact, that
this guy, Jokichi Takamine,

00:17:00.100 --> 00:17:02.290
who's a chemist born
in 1854, thought

00:17:02.290 --> 00:17:05.119
that he could commercialize
it to not just saccharify--

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:07.174
the process of turning
starch into sugar

00:17:07.174 --> 00:17:10.524
is called saccharification--
not just to saccharify rice,

00:17:10.524 --> 00:17:12.300
but barley too.

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:14.290
And this was an incredible
insight on his part.

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:16.980
Because in the late 1880s,
researchers like the Buchner

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:19.579
brothers were still trying to
figure out what enzymes were.

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:22.670
People had just really agreed
that yeast were the things that

00:17:22.670 --> 00:17:24.990
did fermentation
about 20 years before.

00:17:24.990 --> 00:17:28.730
That was the discovery that
put Louis Pasteur on the map,

00:17:28.730 --> 00:17:29.580
saying, yeah, no.

00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:32.132
I'm pretty sure it's
the yeast, you guys.

00:17:32.132 --> 00:17:32.840
Think about that.

00:17:32.840 --> 00:17:36.840
10,000 years of
using the process,

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:39.960
of making fermented and
distilled stuff, and nobody

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:45.130
knew what was doing it
until the 1860s, 1870s.

00:17:45.130 --> 00:17:48.310
And nobody knew how it
worked until much later.

00:17:48.310 --> 00:17:52.150
It's the beginning of
biochemistry, this realization.

00:17:52.150 --> 00:17:53.100
Fermentation.

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:56.330
Yeast converting
sugar to ethanol.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:17:58.820
Takamine thought that he
could convert that process

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:00.130
and commercialize it.

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:03.690
And he actually figured out
how to grow koji on rice bran--

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:06.497
a throwaway product the
sake makers didn't want.

00:18:06.497 --> 00:18:08.580
It was cheaper, it would
actually make more sugar.

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:10.960
And if you're a big distiller,
sugar is actually money.

00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:13.418
You want more sugar because
you get more ethanol out of it.

00:18:13.418 --> 00:18:15.980
He was hired by the
Whiskey Trust-- which

00:18:15.980 --> 00:18:19.145
before prohibition was the
largest distiller in the world,

00:18:19.145 --> 00:18:21.020
it was the American
distilling conglomerate--

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:22.980
to come to the US,
build the facility,

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:25.140
and try to commercialize
that process here,

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:28.030
to make whiskey without malt.

00:18:28.030 --> 00:18:30.410
Zero malt scotch,
instead of single malt.

00:18:34.357 --> 00:18:36.940
His English language biographer
is a woman named Joan Bennett.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:38.606
And she points out
he came pretty close,

00:18:38.606 --> 00:18:43.550
they actually sold a product for
a while called Banzai, again,

00:18:43.550 --> 00:18:45.690
a little bit on the nose.

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:47.096
But things didn't work out.

00:18:47.096 --> 00:18:48.470
One of his facilities
burned down

00:18:48.470 --> 00:18:49.750
under mysterious
circumstances, you

00:18:49.750 --> 00:18:51.625
can imagine the people
who made malt were not

00:18:51.625 --> 00:18:53.980
so happy about this idea.

00:18:53.980 --> 00:18:55.880
And the relationship
with the Whiskey Trust

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:58.090
fell apart, it didn't work out.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:19:02.040
But so we still today
have this process where

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:06.212
we malt to make
whiskey and make beer.

00:19:06.212 --> 00:19:07.920
I don't want you to
feel too bad for him.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:09.710
He took his process
and turned it

00:19:09.710 --> 00:19:13.526
into what Joan Bennett calls
the Alka Seltzer the 1890s,

00:19:13.526 --> 00:19:14.900
this stuff, pocket
Taka-Diastase.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:16.410
And he got so rich
that Parke Davis,

00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:18.160
the pharmaceutical
company, bought it out.

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:21.134
Oh, I should say one thing
that made Takamine unique was

00:19:21.134 --> 00:19:22.800
that unlike most
scientists of the time,

00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:25.980
he didn't mind
patenting his processes.

00:19:25.980 --> 00:19:28.120
So the process for
making that koji stuff

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:31.190
was the first English
language biotechnology patent,

00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:33.280
depending on how you
count that kind of stuff.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:36.940
Eventually Parke Davis bought
the copyright on this stuff

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:38.100
and set him up in a lab.

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:39.490
They wanted him
to figure out how

00:19:39.490 --> 00:19:42.500
to isolate another strange and
wondrous chemical that nobody

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:43.685
knew how it worked.

00:19:43.685 --> 00:19:45.560
At the time they were
calling it epinephrine.

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:48.610
He figured out the process
and named it adrenalin.

00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:51.560
And he patented that too, which
led to a bunch of lawsuits,

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:53.480
because they made so much money.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:57.624
Eventually, a judge named
Learned Hand in 1911 said,

00:19:57.624 --> 00:19:59.290
you guys got to leave
Parke Davis alone.

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:03.446
It is in fact legal to patent
a naturally occurring product.

00:20:03.446 --> 00:20:04.320
This is the decision.

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:08.090
This is the basis for the
modern biotechnology industry,

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:09.470
because of koji.

00:20:09.470 --> 00:20:12.420
Because of the failure
of koji, really.

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:13.670
Takamine got so rich.

00:20:13.670 --> 00:20:15.851
He moved to New York, he
had a beautiful mansion.

00:20:15.851 --> 00:20:18.100
He was kind of an unofficial
technological ambassador.

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:20.350
And eventually it was his
money that paid for these.

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:22.225
These are the cherry
trees in Washington, DC.

00:20:22.225 --> 00:20:27.160
He's the guy who bought
these, the 2,000 cherry trees.

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:32.650
All right, so I'm going
to jump from here back

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:39.350
about 2,000 years to this
place, Ancient Alexandria.

00:20:39.350 --> 00:20:41.055
You know Alexandria,
the library.

00:20:44.170 --> 00:20:48.580
All that Caesar, Mark
Antony, Cleopatra drama.

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:49.880
The lighthouse.

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:54.110
Founded by Alexander the Great,
it's the first modern city.

00:20:54.110 --> 00:20:55.630
It's built on a
gridiron, designed

00:20:55.630 --> 00:20:57.480
to take advantage of prevailing
winds off the desert.

00:20:57.480 --> 00:20:59.438
It has a beautiful
lighthouse, it has plumbing,

00:20:59.438 --> 00:21:01.920
it has the library
that I mentioned.

00:21:01.920 --> 00:21:04.290
It has automatons,
they loved automatons.

00:21:04.290 --> 00:21:07.530
They had steam engines and if
you would open a temple door,

00:21:07.530 --> 00:21:09.510
and then the robot
god in the back

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:11.340
would move and
catch the sunlight,

00:21:11.340 --> 00:21:15.440
you could put a coin into
a slot and a robot bird

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:18.140
would sing a song, and the
temple fire would light up.

00:21:18.140 --> 00:21:19.390
They loved that kind of stuff.

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:20.630
They had parades for it.

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:22.480
This is a city of engineers.

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:23.396
They're technologists.

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:28.164
And more than that though,
they're alchemists.

00:21:28.164 --> 00:21:30.330
One of the things that the
labs there are working on

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:31.120
is alchemy.

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:33.010
Now alchemy gets kind
of-- in my opinion--

00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:33.820
it gets kind of a raw deal.

00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:35.430
Because what we know
about alchemy is like, oh,

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:36.780
they were trying to
convert lead into gold.

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:38.690
It's the Middle Ages,
they're con artists

00:21:38.690 --> 00:21:40.750
looking for eternal
life, Harry Potter stuff.

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:41.800
Fine.

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:44.750
Philosophically, they were
wrong about almost everything.

00:21:44.750 --> 00:21:46.380
But methodologically
they weren't.

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:49.340
What they were doing was
inventing the infrastructure

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:50.780
for modern science.

00:21:50.780 --> 00:21:55.550
Critically coming up with a lab
and experimentation on nature

00:21:55.550 --> 00:21:57.210
and the stuff in that lab.

00:21:57.210 --> 00:22:01.840
So one of the most famous
of them is this woman.

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:04.700
This is Maria the Jewess.

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:08.192
We only know mostly-- I
know, I didn't name her.

00:22:08.192 --> 00:22:09.044
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:09.044 --> 00:22:11.130
We know about her mostly
from a biographer who

00:22:11.130 --> 00:22:14.612
wrote about her much later,
named Zosimos the Panopolitan.

00:22:14.612 --> 00:22:16.580
Gotta get a "the" in my name.

00:22:16.580 --> 00:22:17.440
Right?

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:19.787
How awesome would that be?

00:22:19.787 --> 00:22:21.620
And he never really
said when she was alive,

00:22:21.620 --> 00:22:25.265
but people think roughly the
turn of the first millennium.

00:22:25.265 --> 00:22:28.380
Do you know what a bain-marie
is or a marienbad in a lab?

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:31.120
A laboratory double-boiler?

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:32.552
She invented that.

00:22:32.552 --> 00:22:34.382
It's ascribed to her.

00:22:34.382 --> 00:22:36.340
It's not the only piece
of laboratory equipment

00:22:36.340 --> 00:22:36.990
she invented.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:40.080
She also came up with this.

00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:44.180
The one on the left is called a
kerotakis, the one on the right

00:22:44.180 --> 00:22:45.480
is a tribikos.

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:48.727
Forgive my ancient Greek,
my pronunciation's terrible.

00:22:48.727 --> 00:22:50.810
In Arabic you would call
these things put together

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:53.500
an al-anbiq or an alembic.

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:55.370
This is a still.

00:22:55.370 --> 00:22:57.150
She came up with it.

00:22:57.150 --> 00:22:59.879
She wanted to heat stuff
and separate it out.

00:22:59.879 --> 00:23:01.420
There's some
disagreement about this.

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:04.040
The still could have been
first invented in China.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:08.010
But the way I want you
to think about a still

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:10.334
is as a separation
technology, high technology

00:23:10.334 --> 00:23:11.250
for separating things.

00:23:11.250 --> 00:23:12.416
So how do we separate stuff?

00:23:12.416 --> 00:23:14.547
Filtration, you
separate things by size.

00:23:14.547 --> 00:23:16.630
Centrifugation, you're
separating things by weight

00:23:16.630 --> 00:23:17.100
essentially.

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:18.850
You increase gravity
and the heavier stuff

00:23:18.850 --> 00:23:20.220
falls to the bottom.

00:23:20.220 --> 00:23:22.300
Modern practices, gas
chromatography or gel

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:25.750
electrophoresis, you separate
things by electrical charge.

00:23:25.750 --> 00:23:27.320
What a still does
is separate things

00:23:27.320 --> 00:23:30.470
based on evaporation
pressure, based on volatility.

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:33.280
More volatile stuff-- things
that evaporate easily--

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:34.480
go over the top first.

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:37.050
Things that evaporate with
more energy, go over later.

00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:38.899
And you can separate things out.

00:23:38.899 --> 00:23:40.940
You can get rid of things
you don't want and keep

00:23:40.940 --> 00:23:43.167
the things you do,
like ethanol and water.

00:23:43.167 --> 00:23:45.500
Different molecules evaporate
at different temperatures.

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:47.265
Now what--

00:23:47.265 --> 00:23:48.140
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:48.140 --> 00:23:49.070
ADAM ROGERS: --No,
its fine, I'll stop.

00:23:49.070 --> 00:23:50.070
Whatever, it's cool.

00:23:50.070 --> 00:23:54.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:54.700 --> 00:23:58.847
Probably what Maria was trying
to do did not involve booze.

00:23:58.847 --> 00:24:00.680
They had access to Roman
wine in Alexandria,

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:02.800
but she was probably putting
in stuff like sulfur.

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:06.850
The alchemists were
interested in the spirits

00:24:06.850 --> 00:24:08.700
in inanimate objects,
right, that's

00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:10.619
where we get that word too.

00:24:10.619 --> 00:24:13.160
So she was putting in metals
and liquids and stuff like that.

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:14.800
She did figure out you
need to use copper,

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:15.930
and you need to use solder.

00:24:15.930 --> 00:24:17.460
And you need to keep
the heat insulated

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:18.918
and keep the heat
from getting out,

00:24:18.918 --> 00:24:20.530
all the basic tenets
of distilling.

00:24:20.530 --> 00:24:23.130
Nobody really knows if anybody
ever put that wine in the still

00:24:23.130 --> 00:24:24.000
to see what would happen.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.280
I like to think of her lab as
being like a graduate student

00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:26.710
lab though.

00:24:26.710 --> 00:24:28.082
And I figure, come
on, they must have

00:24:28.082 --> 00:24:29.665
put-- they were
drinking all the time.

00:24:29.665 --> 00:24:31.955
They put booze in
the still, right?

00:24:31.955 --> 00:24:34.580
It's not clear whether they did
or not, there's other evidence.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:37.170
The technology either spreads
or gets invented somewhere else.

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:42.320
There's evidence of it between
150 AD and 400 AD in India.

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:45.725
There's some reference to it in
China in 980, wine that burns.

00:24:45.725 --> 00:24:47.725
The alcohol content would
have to be high enough

00:24:47.725 --> 00:24:50.530
for it to burn so that it
would have to be distilled.

00:24:50.530 --> 00:24:53.010
In about 1000 AD you
see references in Russia

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:55.902
to bread wine, vodka.

00:24:55.902 --> 00:24:58.670
In the 1200s there's
a big shot alchemist

00:24:58.670 --> 00:25:02.220
named Albertus Magnus who
writes about burning water.

00:25:02.220 --> 00:25:04.610
But in the mid 1280s,
this guy is the one

00:25:04.610 --> 00:25:05.860
who really puts it on the map.

00:25:05.860 --> 00:25:09.230
He's a physician from Bologna
named Taddeo Alderotti.

00:25:09.230 --> 00:25:11.720
He writes a book called
"Consilia Medicinalia"

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:14.410
where he describes the
process for making something

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:18.310
called aqua vita,
the water of life.

00:25:18.310 --> 00:25:20.900
And this stuff was magic.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:23.730
It would cure diseases,
it would relieve pain,

00:25:23.730 --> 00:25:26.415
it would fix bad breath, it
would purify spoiled wine,

00:25:26.415 --> 00:25:28.940
it would preserve meat,
you could draw essences out

00:25:28.940 --> 00:25:30.950
of plants and smell them later.

00:25:30.950 --> 00:25:33.510
For the first time, these
people who basically were just

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:40.396
witch doctors finally had a
chemical that did something.

00:25:40.396 --> 00:25:41.520
They could make a medicine.

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:42.519
It felt like a medicine.

00:25:42.519 --> 00:25:45.120
And in fact, it was just
about the only medicine

00:25:45.120 --> 00:25:48.286
that they gave anybody who
was dying of the Black Plague.

00:25:48.286 --> 00:25:49.910
Because they didn't
have anything else,

00:25:49.910 --> 00:25:55.012
which contributed to the spread
of alcoholism across Europe.

00:25:55.012 --> 00:25:56.470
What Alderotti also
figured out was

00:25:56.470 --> 00:25:57.969
that if you added
a serpentine coil

00:25:57.969 --> 00:26:00.510
from the top of a still and then
immersed that in cold water,

00:26:00.510 --> 00:26:02.030
the vapors that were
coming out of that still

00:26:02.030 --> 00:26:04.370
would condense more quickly,
and you'd get liquid.

00:26:04.370 --> 00:26:07.890
He put the capping
technology on top of a still.

00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:09.780
And it spread across Europe.

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:11.580
Everyone starts distilling.

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:14.110
You end up with
places like this.

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:15.500
This is, I think, Jim Beam.

00:26:15.500 --> 00:26:17.180
That's the top of the
still at Jim Beam.

00:26:17.180 --> 00:26:18.470
That's a column still.

00:26:18.470 --> 00:26:20.880
It goes down six
floors from there.

00:26:20.880 --> 00:26:23.920
It's 60 or 70 feet tall.

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:24.649
Or this.

00:26:24.649 --> 00:26:26.190
This is St George
spirits in Alameda.

00:26:26.190 --> 00:26:29.490
It's one of my
favorite distilleries.

00:26:29.490 --> 00:26:31.520
And this is a new one.

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:34.934
This is New Caledonia
in Washington, DC.

00:26:34.934 --> 00:26:36.600
The columns are an
interesting addition,

00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:39.200
because what the columns do is
let you finesse that separation

00:26:39.200 --> 00:26:40.027
process further.

00:26:40.027 --> 00:26:41.860
The stuff you're
distilling goes in the top,

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:43.750
steam goes up the
bottom, and the chemicals

00:26:43.750 --> 00:26:45.040
fractionate out in the middle.

00:26:45.040 --> 00:26:47.870
So whatever thing you want,
you can put an outlet pipe

00:26:47.870 --> 00:26:51.060
at a different height
on those columns

00:26:51.060 --> 00:26:52.560
and get out the
stuff that you want.

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:55.170
It was a later addition
to the process.

00:26:58.634 --> 00:27:01.300
Basically, you put the stuff you
want to distill in that big pot

00:27:01.300 --> 00:27:02.500
and set it boiling.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:04.480
And then it's plumbing,
you turn it on.

00:27:08.015 --> 00:27:10.390
Scroll down a second, I'm
forgetting one important point.

00:27:15.520 --> 00:27:19.080
So that precision is important,
because otherwise you

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.600
have to just time your
process of distilling,

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:24.190
so you don't have like
methanol in it, which is toxic.

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:25.700
Or you don't have kind
of yuckier flavors, which

00:27:25.700 --> 00:27:27.658
is what comes out at the
end of a distillation.

00:27:27.658 --> 00:27:30.437
You just want the middle,
the heart they call it.

00:27:30.437 --> 00:27:32.812
But the important thing I want
you to take away from this

00:27:32.812 --> 00:27:35.179
is the precision
that finally evolved.

00:27:35.179 --> 00:27:36.970
We go from this natural
process that nobody

00:27:36.970 --> 00:27:38.650
knows how it works
to one that we begin

00:27:38.650 --> 00:27:41.360
to identify how it works and
can take control of, or at least

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:45.180
domesticate, to taking
the science of that

00:27:45.180 --> 00:27:47.180
and turning it into a
technological process, one

00:27:47.180 --> 00:27:50.120
that's precise, and one
that we use all the time.

00:27:50.120 --> 00:27:51.971
That's what's happened there.

00:27:51.971 --> 00:27:53.720
I have a couple more
things I want to say,

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:56.680
but I feel like I
would be cheating you

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:58.980
if I didn't talk a little
bit about hangovers.

00:27:58.980 --> 00:28:00.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:00.880
Is that true?

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:01.680
I don't want to
just get out of here

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:03.180
without telling you
about hangovers.

00:28:04.467 --> 00:28:06.050
Nobody knows anything
about hangovers.

00:28:08.621 --> 00:28:09.620
That's not totally true.

00:28:09.620 --> 00:28:10.890
There's not a lot of science.

00:28:10.890 --> 00:28:15.330
Here's one of the things I
love about the science of booze

00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:17.830
is of all of the
recreational drugs

00:28:17.830 --> 00:28:20.640
that people take-- whatever
your feelings about the legality

00:28:20.640 --> 00:28:23.350
and morality of that are,
we take a lot of them.

00:28:23.350 --> 00:28:25.399
Of all of those
drugs, the only one

00:28:25.399 --> 00:28:27.940
for which scientists have not
articulated a mechanism for how

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:30.310
it works in the
brain is ethanol,

00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:32.502
the one we have
taken the longest.

00:28:32.502 --> 00:28:33.460
They don't really know.

00:28:33.460 --> 00:28:35.502
They've got some ideas.

00:28:35.502 --> 00:28:37.460
If you ask a researcher
who studies this stuff,

00:28:37.460 --> 00:28:39.890
well how does marijuana work--
or methamphetamine or opium.

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:41.490
They know the receptor, they
know the region of the brain.

00:28:41.490 --> 00:28:42.906
They kind of know
what's going on.

00:28:42.906 --> 00:28:43.860
Ethanol?

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:44.675
We got an idea.

00:28:44.675 --> 00:28:48.829
A couple of notions for
receptors, reaches the brain.

00:28:48.829 --> 00:28:50.620
Partially that may be
because if you really

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:53.200
press a neuroscientist on
this, they don't really

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:55.407
know how the brain works either.

00:28:55.407 --> 00:28:56.490
They have some good ideas.

00:28:56.490 --> 00:28:59.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:01.780
A lot of the research
in alcohol and how

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:06.025
it affects the human
body is on dependency

00:29:06.025 --> 00:29:07.730
and on binge drinking.

00:29:07.730 --> 00:29:08.752
As you would imagine.

00:29:08.752 --> 00:29:10.460
Those are problems,
and they kill people,

00:29:10.460 --> 00:29:11.990
and they hurt people, and
they cost a lot of money.

00:29:11.990 --> 00:29:14.115
So researchers are trying
to figure that stuff out.

00:29:14.115 --> 00:29:18.300
But the research on-- I
try to think of my book

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:22.330
as taking place about three
sips into your second round.

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:24.010
The pivot point of
my book is the moment

00:29:24.010 --> 00:29:25.510
when a bartender
serves you a drink.

00:29:25.510 --> 00:29:30.270
It's about what happens when you
have one drink or two drinks.

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:33.410
But sometimes you mess up.

00:29:33.410 --> 00:29:37.540
A hangover is a symptom of that.

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:40.065
There is not a lot of
science on hangovers.

00:29:40.065 --> 00:29:42.440
I will tell you that almost
everything that they told you

00:29:42.440 --> 00:29:47.390
the day before your first
weekend night of college

00:29:47.390 --> 00:29:49.574
is wrong, or at least unproven.

00:29:49.574 --> 00:29:50.990
So you're sitting
there and you're

00:29:50.990 --> 00:29:52.560
thinking it's dehydration.

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:54.012
It's not dehydration.

00:29:54.012 --> 00:29:55.720
Your electrolyte levels
go back to normal

00:29:55.720 --> 00:29:57.136
when you're still
hungover and you

00:29:57.136 --> 00:29:59.617
can rehydrate and still
have the hangover.

00:29:59.617 --> 00:30:01.450
People think that because
alcohol suppresses

00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:04.060
a hormone called vasopressin,
it's an anti-diuretic hormone,

00:30:04.060 --> 00:30:06.560
it's the hormone that keeps
you from peeing all the time.

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:08.400
Had too much alcohol, now
you're peeing all the time.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:11.070
Plus, you're not drinking water,
you're drinking beer, whatever.

00:30:11.070 --> 00:30:11.770
So yeah, you're dehydrated.

00:30:11.770 --> 00:30:12.940
But that's not the hangover.

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:14.440
People think that
it's too much sugar.

00:30:14.440 --> 00:30:14.939
It's not.

00:30:14.939 --> 00:30:17.380
Your sugar levels are
fine when you're hungover.

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:21.630
People think that it is, oh, I
had impure alcohol, congeners.

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:24.420
I should have had clear
liquor instead of bourbon.

00:30:24.420 --> 00:30:24.920
It's not.

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:27.650
You get just as hungover with
vodka as you do with bourbon.

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:29.920
Some people report a worse
hangover with bourbon,

00:30:29.920 --> 00:30:32.110
but it's mostly anecdotal.

00:30:32.110 --> 00:30:34.431
More complicated,
acetaldehyde toxicity.

00:30:34.431 --> 00:30:35.930
No. acetaldehyde
is hard to measure,

00:30:35.930 --> 00:30:37.820
but your acetaldehyde
levels are zero.

00:30:37.820 --> 00:30:38.840
Methanol toxicity.

00:30:38.840 --> 00:30:40.310
There's some methanol
in anything fermented

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:40.810
and distilled.

00:30:40.810 --> 00:30:42.060
The symptoms look
like they overlap.

00:30:42.060 --> 00:30:43.630
It would be great,
because it's a good excuse

00:30:43.630 --> 00:30:45.400
for the hair of the dog-- I
can explain that if you want.

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:46.720
But it's probably not methanol.

00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:47.553
Nobody really knows.

00:30:47.553 --> 00:30:50.900
What it looks like is an
inflammatory response.

00:30:50.900 --> 00:30:53.516
Like if you have the flu,
you feel aches, you feel kind

00:30:53.516 --> 00:30:54.890
of stupid, you
have gut problems,

00:30:54.890 --> 00:30:57.640
your head aches-- it also has
some overlap symptomatology

00:30:57.640 --> 00:30:58.840
with migraine.

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:01.090
So there are few
things that have ever

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:06.090
been shown in real studies to
have an effect on a hangover.

00:31:06.090 --> 00:31:07.590
One of them is a
drug called Clotem.

00:31:07.590 --> 00:31:10.760
It's kind of a super high
powered anti-inflammatory

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:13.490
that they prescribe for
migraines primarily.

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:16.010
You can't get it in
the United States.

00:31:16.010 --> 00:31:17.564
I tried.

00:31:17.564 --> 00:31:19.980
Asked a neurologist, she was
like, I'm not prescribing it.

00:31:19.980 --> 00:31:22.450
It's not on the Pharmacopoeia,
and plus no I wouldn't.

00:31:22.450 --> 00:31:24.290
That's stupid, I'm
not doing that.

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:25.748
I tried to get it
from a friend who

00:31:25.748 --> 00:31:27.310
lived in England,
to get her to lie

00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:29.670
to her doctor on the
National Health Service.

00:31:29.670 --> 00:31:31.570
She was like, no, I'm
not going to do that.

00:31:31.570 --> 00:31:32.592
So I've never tried it.

00:31:32.592 --> 00:31:34.550
But a few things that
are sold over the counter

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:36.900
here have been shown
in studies to work.

00:31:36.900 --> 00:31:41.320
Pyritinol the left is
vitamin B-6 analog.

00:31:41.320 --> 00:31:45.230
It's two B-6 molecules
connected by a sulfur atom.

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:49.070
The LiverCare thing is
an Ayurvedic therapy

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:51.180
that's only been shown
to work in studies done

00:31:51.180 --> 00:31:55.460
by the company that makes it, so
take that for what it's worth.

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:58.280
And one on the far right
is prickly pear cactus

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:00.530
extract, which kind of
makes sense because it has

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:03.070
mild anti-inflammatory
effects, prickly pear does.

00:32:03.070 --> 00:32:05.429
It also makes a
very good burrito.

00:32:05.429 --> 00:32:06.970
The one in the middle
is interesting,

00:32:06.970 --> 00:32:09.590
because the one in the middle
is-- they call it BluCetin.

00:32:09.590 --> 00:32:11.673
You can't see that well
in the picture, I'm sorry.

00:32:11.673 --> 00:32:15.090
But it's made from a molecule
called dihydromyricetin, which

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:19.750
is an extract of a plant called
oriental raisin or hovenia,

00:32:19.750 --> 00:32:22.060
which is used to
treat alcohol problems

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:24.750
in the traditional
Chinese pharmacopoeia.

00:32:24.750 --> 00:32:27.050
But a lab at UCLA
looked into it,

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:31.050
and it does seem to affect
a receptor in the brain that

00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:33.790
looks like it's the target for
alcohol in that relevant range

00:32:33.790 --> 00:32:36.440
that I was talking about,
in that up to 0.06.

00:32:36.440 --> 00:32:38.670
Like the drink and a half range.

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:41.300
It's a receptor
that's involved in how

00:32:41.300 --> 00:32:43.980
we feel benzodiazepines
drugs, like Valium.

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:46.250
And that makes sense too,
because benzodiazepines

00:32:46.250 --> 00:32:48.330
and alcohol always have
a synergistic effect.

00:32:48.330 --> 00:32:50.705
They'll tell you if you're
taking a benzodiazepines don't

00:32:50.705 --> 00:32:53.750
drink also, because it will
knock you right on your ass.

00:32:53.750 --> 00:32:55.370
So that's a target
that some people

00:32:55.370 --> 00:32:58.356
