00:34:13.350 --> 00:34:16.489
So I was in Japan a couple of
weeks ago, family vacation.

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:20.730
And the Imperial Hotel
in Tokyo right now

00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:24.380
is this giant, brutalist,
skyscraper-looking place,

00:34:24.380 --> 00:34:25.080
very ugly.

00:34:25.080 --> 00:34:27.547
But the original
Imperial Hotel in Tokyo

00:34:27.547 --> 00:34:28.880
was built by Frank Lloyd Wright.

00:34:28.880 --> 00:34:32.389
It was one of the most
beautiful buildings anywhere.

00:34:32.389 --> 00:34:34.139
Like so many Frank
Lloyd Wright buildings,

00:34:34.139 --> 00:34:37.480
it fell down in the 1960s.

00:34:37.480 --> 00:34:40.710
Not a good engineer,
Frank Lloyd Wright.

00:34:40.710 --> 00:34:42.600
But the one place
in the building

00:34:42.600 --> 00:34:45.989
that still has the original
Frank Lloyd Wright appointments

00:34:45.989 --> 00:34:47.639
is the old bar.

00:34:47.639 --> 00:34:49.900
So you can go to the old
Imperial Bar in the hotel,

00:34:49.900 --> 00:34:52.429
and it has beautiful
Frank Lloyd Wright wall

00:34:52.429 --> 00:34:55.305
hangings and the
tiles and stuff.

00:34:55.305 --> 00:34:57.430
It's really nice and it's
a very nice cocktail bar,

00:34:57.430 --> 00:34:59.470
so I wanted to go.

00:34:59.470 --> 00:35:03.314
Because I-- I ordered this
drink call the Gemini,

00:35:03.314 --> 00:35:04.980
it's their house
drink, it was terrible.

00:35:04.980 --> 00:35:06.521
But the coaster's
really nice, right?

00:35:06.521 --> 00:35:07.710
It's a beautiful coaster.

00:35:07.710 --> 00:35:09.835
Because I wanted to feel
the connection to history,

00:35:09.835 --> 00:35:13.610
to a Frank Lloyd Wright
building and to the history

00:35:13.610 --> 00:35:14.350
of cocktails.

00:35:14.350 --> 00:35:17.390
And that's a thing that
alcohol will give you,

00:35:17.390 --> 00:35:20.352
is that connection down
through shallow time,

00:35:20.352 --> 00:35:22.810
with Frank Lloyd Wright and
then deeper with the people who

00:35:22.810 --> 00:35:25.490
first started making
gin, for example,

00:35:25.490 --> 00:35:27.790
which human beings
were making 1,000 years

00:35:27.790 --> 00:35:30.670
before they knew how it worked.

00:35:30.670 --> 00:35:33.330
They were making it without
really knowing how to make it.

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:35.788
They still don't really know
why we taste it the way we do.

00:35:35.788 --> 00:35:41.012
We make this stuff, and
it affects our senses--

00:35:41.012 --> 00:35:42.220
our sense of smell and taste.

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:43.886
And you and I would
taste the same thing

00:35:43.886 --> 00:35:47.464
and if we told each other
that it tasted the same to us,

00:35:47.464 --> 00:35:49.630
we might be talking about
actually different flavors

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:52.005
in our heads, or we might
taste entirely different things

00:35:52.005 --> 00:35:53.550
in it, and nobody
really knows why.

00:35:53.550 --> 00:35:56.060
It alters our bodies,
it changes our minds,

00:35:56.060 --> 00:35:57.900
and nobody really knows how.

00:35:57.900 --> 00:36:00.070
They're working on it.

00:36:00.070 --> 00:36:02.679
We taste it differently, we
feel its effects differently,

00:36:02.679 --> 00:36:04.970
every culture that uses it
has different rituals for it

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:08.170
and manifest the effects
of that differently.

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:12.840
We have cracked open yeast
and the other microbes that

00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:15.340
are responsible for it and begun
to understand that biology.

00:36:15.340 --> 00:36:17.361
Yeast are an incredibly
important model organism

00:36:17.361 --> 00:36:17.860
in science.

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:19.250
They were the
first organism that

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:22.700
was ever a genetic sequence for.

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:26.660
So we've gone from the
agricultural process

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:28.970
of domesticating a microbe
we only understood vaguely

00:36:28.970 --> 00:36:32.550
to the cold precision
of genetic engineering.

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:35.770
But really, we were making
booze before we had science,

00:36:35.770 --> 00:36:38.140
much less before we
had booze science.

00:36:38.140 --> 00:36:39.910
Now that we have
all that science,

00:36:39.910 --> 00:36:43.032
now that we understand
it a little bit more,

00:36:43.032 --> 00:36:45.490
I don't want you to think that
that makes the stuff that we

00:36:45.490 --> 00:36:49.450
drink less magical,
less amazing.

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:53.470
I'm, I guess, paraphrasing
Arthur C Clarke a little bit.

00:36:53.470 --> 00:36:56.250
Magic is just
advanced technology.

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:58.020
The science that we
use to make this stuff

00:36:58.020 --> 00:37:00.160
is what makes the magic.

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:02.597
What I want to argue, and
what I want to leave you with,

00:37:02.597 --> 00:37:04.680
is this notion that when
you are tasting something

00:37:04.680 --> 00:37:07.220
that you're drinking-- whatever
it is, if you're tasting

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:11.610
the strawberry notes in a
nice glass of white wine

00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:15.149
or the smoke in a
peated Ila whisky--

00:37:15.149 --> 00:37:17.440
that while you are tasting
all those things what you're

00:37:17.440 --> 00:37:19.856
actually tasting, those flavors
and aromas you are tasting

00:37:19.856 --> 00:37:21.701
is civilization.

00:37:21.701 --> 00:37:22.200
Thank you.

