00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:09.120
AUDIENCE: Can I just buy
Domino sugar and make--

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:11.160
ADAM ROGERS: Yeah, that's rum.

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:13.670
A lot of the rum that we
drink-- I mean, not exactly.

00:38:13.670 --> 00:38:17.250
Well, let me calibrate
that slightly.

00:38:17.250 --> 00:38:18.560
Most rum is made from molasses.

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:21.260
Molasses is a byproduct
of processing sugar cane

00:38:21.260 --> 00:38:22.760
into sugar.

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:25.650
If you want to make
white powdered sugar,

00:38:25.650 --> 00:38:27.830
you end up with a
lot of molasses,

00:38:27.830 --> 00:38:29.220
which ferments really easily.

00:38:29.220 --> 00:38:31.580
In fact, it ferments so
easily that you really

00:38:31.580 --> 00:38:34.569
want your rum distillery next
to your sugar cane processing

00:38:34.569 --> 00:38:36.360
plant, because it comes
right out of there.

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:37.450
And you've got to get
it into the still,

00:38:37.450 --> 00:38:39.420
because otherwise all the
wild stuff's going to colonize

00:38:39.420 --> 00:38:40.220
and it will go bad.

00:38:40.220 --> 00:38:42.730
You can also make a drink
called Rhum Agricole.

00:38:42.730 --> 00:38:44.711
Rhum Agricole is
