00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:30.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:30.250 --> 00:39:32.740
What else?

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:34.650
AUDIENCE: So a
lot of the liquors

00:39:34.650 --> 00:39:37.249
have precursors, like
whiskey is distilled beer.

00:39:37.249 --> 00:39:38.040
ADAM ROGERS: Right.

00:39:38.040 --> 00:39:39.730
AUDIENCE: And brandy
is distilled--

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:40.480
ADAM ROGERS: Wine.

00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:42.520
AUDIENCE: --Wine.

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:45.670
Who thought up vodka?

00:39:45.670 --> 00:39:50.950
ADAM ROGERS: Well, so, a lot
of people who think about booze

00:39:50.950 --> 00:39:54.157
or who write about
it go by category.

00:39:54.157 --> 00:39:55.490
It's a perfectly good heuristic.

00:39:55.490 --> 00:39:58.830
Wine, beer, tequila,
rum, scotch, whatever.

00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:01.330
They write about
a specific thing.

00:40:01.330 --> 00:40:05.800
I'm intentionally forcing
a different heuristic,

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:07.050
which is process.

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:10.140
Which goes-- and this is
the structure of the book.

00:40:10.140 --> 00:40:12.395
Starts with yeast,
goes to sugar,

00:40:12.395 --> 00:40:17.500
you ferment that, you distill
it, you can age it in a barrel.

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.530
Then you taste and smell it.

00:40:19.530 --> 00:40:22.590
Take a drink, has affect on
your body, on your brain.

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:26.470
And any alcohol, any booze
falls under those categories.

00:40:26.470 --> 00:40:30.700
So vodka is easy,
because vodka, you

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:32.780
can use any substrate you want.

00:40:32.780 --> 00:40:35.130
And famously it's oh,
Russians had potatoes.

00:40:35.130 --> 00:40:36.030
But you can make
it out of anything,

00:40:36.030 --> 00:40:37.930
because all you're doing is
running it through the still so

00:40:37.930 --> 00:40:39.429
many times that
you're stripping out

00:40:39.429 --> 00:40:42.420
every molecule, except
ethanol and water.

00:40:42.420 --> 00:40:44.917
In fact, in the United States
if you're selling vodka,

00:40:44.917 --> 00:40:46.500
that's all that's
allowed to be in it.

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:48.200
Those are the only molecules.

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:49.970
It's just H2O and ethanol.

00:40:49.970 --> 00:40:50.960
That's it.

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:55.030
Which is weird, because
they taste different.

00:40:55.030 --> 00:40:57.520
So you go well,
how does that work?

00:40:57.520 --> 00:41:00.100
Maybe the levels of alcohol
are different, sometimes.

00:41:00.100 --> 00:41:04.730
But if they all say 80 proof,
they're all 40% percent ABV.

00:41:04.730 --> 00:41:08.320
If it's all 40% ethanol
molecules and 60% water

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.190
molecules, what's going on?

00:41:10.190 --> 00:41:11.800
Some of it might
just be marketing.

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:13.920
Theater is super
important with booze.

00:41:13.920 --> 00:41:15.295
Marketing in the
theater of-- you

00:41:15.295 --> 00:41:19.420
know, imagine that bottle of red
wine that you had on that trip

00:41:19.420 --> 00:41:22.800
where you got lost and you found
that perfect little trattoria

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:23.314
in Tuscany.

00:41:23.314 --> 00:41:24.730
And you got that
bottle and it was

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:25.850
like the best
bottle of red wine.

00:41:25.850 --> 00:41:26.840
And then you get
the stuff at home

00:41:26.840 --> 00:41:28.798
and watching it in front
of a "Star Trek" rerun

00:41:28.798 --> 00:41:32.580
it doesn't quite--
it's not really as good

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:33.507
out of the Mason jar.

00:41:33.507 --> 00:41:34.840
It's like well, it's still good.

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:35.710
Don't get me wrong.

00:41:35.710 --> 00:41:39.500
Plus this is the one with
the green Orion slave girl.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:42.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:42.780 --> 00:41:44.350
Always makes wine better.

00:41:44.350 --> 00:41:47.620
But there's a hypothesis.

00:41:47.620 --> 00:41:49.990
I have a paper that's
pretty great that

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:52.879
suggests that the relationship
between those molecules

00:41:52.879 --> 00:41:55.170
can change depending on
levels, because the water forms

00:41:55.170 --> 00:41:56.294
what are called clathrates.

00:41:56.294 --> 00:41:59.940
Basically they're
kind of H2O crystals

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:02.340
that surround the ethanol.

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:04.220
And the different
shapes of those crystals

00:42:04.220 --> 00:42:07.900
might be perceptible as a
matter of flavor or aroma.

00:42:07.900 --> 00:42:10.149
It's tantalizing as a paper.

00:42:10.149 --> 00:42:11.690
And it was a pretty
good paper that I

00:42:11.690 --> 00:42:13.240
don't know that
anybody followed up on.

00:42:13.240 --> 00:42:15.905
It also, of course, came out of
a lab in Russia, as you expect.

